# Auto-commit to GitHub

After completing a **major feature**, **bug fix**, or **coherent batch of work**, commit and push to GitHub without waiting for the user to ask — unless they said not to commit in this session.

## When to commit

Commit when **all** of these apply:

- The change is **complete** (build passes if applicable; no half-finished refactor)
- It is **major** or **fix-worthy**: new feature, user-visible bug fix, security fix, broken dev/build restored, or docs for a shipped feature
- **Do not** commit: tiny typos, WIP mid-task, exploratory spikes, or `.env` / secrets / credentials files

## Workflow

1. Run `git status`, `git diff`, and `git log -3 --oneline` (parallel)
2. Stage relevant files — **never** `.env`, `.vapix.credentials.json`, or other gitignored secrets
3. Write a concise commit message (1–2 sentences, focus on **why**)
4. Commit via HEREDOC message
5. **Push** to `origin` on the current branch (`git push origin HEAD`) so GitHub stays in sync

If push fails (auth, network), report the error and leave the local commit; do not force-push.

## Commit message style

Match existing repo tone. Examples:

- `Fix dev server CSP blocking React Refresh in Vite`
- `Add camera web UI proxy and stream connectivity test`
- `Translate UI to English and add menu tab descriptions`

## Split commits

Prefer **one commit per logical unit** when several major items were done in one session (e.g. separate fix vs feature). Avoid one giant commit if changes are clearly unrelated.
